post_cb({"10843755": {"CommentCount": "3", "Body": "<p>This is so-called direct-initialization. In C++, integers are not objects and the expression that you write here is not a constructor. It just initializes a to the value of 32.</p>\n", "CreationDate": "2012-06-01T02:42:39.557", "ParentId": "10843715", "Id": "10843755", "LastActivityDate": "2012-06-01T02:42:39.557", "PostTypeId": "2", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "1380680"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_10843715_10843772_0": {"length": 15, "quality": 0.6818181818181818, "section_id": 3295}}, "n3337": {"so_10843715_10843772_0": {"length": 15, "quality": 0.6818181818181818, "section_id": 3165}}}, "10843772": {"CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>This is best described in:     </p>\n<p><strong>C++03 8.5 Initializers</strong><br>\n<strong>Para 12 &amp; 13:</strong> </br></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_10843715_10843772_0\">.......<br>\n  The initialization that occurs in new expressions (5.3.4), static_cast expressions (5.2.9), functional notation type conversions (5.2.3), and base and member initializers (12.6.2) is called<br>\n<em>direct-initialization</em> and is equivalent to the form</br></br></p>\n<p id=\"so_10843715_10843772_1\">T x(a);    </p>\n<p id=\"so_10843715_10843772_2\">If T is a scalar type, then a declaration of the form</p>\n<pre><code>T x = { a };\n</code></pre>\n<p id=\"so_10843715_10843772_3\">is equivalent to   </p>\n<pre><code>T x = a;\n</code></pre>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In the question the type is <code>int</code> which is a scalar type.</p>\n", "CreationDate": "2012-06-01T02:46:28.190", "ParentId": "10843715", "Id": "10843772", "LastActivityDate": "2012-06-01T02:46:28.190", "PostTypeId": "2", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "452307"}, "10843715": {"CreationDate": "2012-06-01T02:34:37.523", "ViewCount": "1241", "Id": "10843715", "AcceptedAnswerId": "10843772", "Score": "0", "Title": "Constructor Initialization of primitive data types in CPP", "LastEditorUserId": "141719", "CommentCount": "2", "Body": "<p>In cpp, we can have primitive data-types initialized as </p>\n<pre><code>int a(32);\n</code></pre>\n<p>How does this constructor initialisation work? Does C++ treat it as an object?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><initialization>", "LastEditDate": "2012-06-01T03:26:55.207", "LastActivityDate": "2012-06-01T03:26:55.207", "PostTypeId": "1", "AnswerCount": "2", "OwnerUserId": "619109"}});